{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"599ce631-50bb-4506-bc7c-85d29e3c0b04","content":"Here's the `mcp.json` configuration for VS Code (place it at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- Make sure your MCP server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport).\n\nAfter saving, open the Command Palette → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected. Copilot agent mode will then discover and call your server's tools automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"661ef408-2f11-47a6-a556-622e8d0adc84","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure an `mcp.json` file to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me check their project to give accurate advice.","outputTokens":296},"id":"1195b7bf-8d9d-40c3-9e5d-74ea703b1f91","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:14.716Z","parentId":"57e4220c-5191-4cc8-af4f-8c32984e011c"}
